That he was alive in 1444, when Corstorphine was erected into a Collegiate Church, is at least highly probable: the continuator of the Scotiehronicon, circa 1447, in his list of Collegiate Churches, names Cor- storphine ‘⁶ cujus fundator dominus <Iohannes Forster pater ;” but this does not imply his being then alive. His son, the second Sir John Fon-ester, who had been infest during his father's life in 1430, is said to have died before 15th September 1454, but this date is not well ascertained. We find, however, that the grandson, Sir Alexander Fon-ester, was in possession of the estates in the year 1463)
